t, England":"Dorset, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"about 0870–":"circa 0870–Overleden","0870–Male":"0870–Overleden","0874–Female":"0874–Overleden","0890–0989":"0890–0989","0844–Male":"0844–Overleden","0849–Female":"0849–Overleden","980":"0980","0874":"0874","0870":"0870","about 0870":"circa 0870","0890":"0890","0849":"0849","0989":"0989","927":"0927","0844":"0844","Abergavenny, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Abergavenny, Monmouthshire, Wales","Much Marcle, Herefordshire, England":"Much Marcle, Herefordshire, England","Dorset, England":"Dorset, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 0870–":"about 0870–Deceased","0870–Male":"0870–Deceased","0874–Female":"0874–Deceased","0890–0989":"0890–0989","0844–Male":"0844–Deceased","0849–Female":"0849–Deceased","980":"0980","0874":"0874","0870":"0870","about 0870":"about 0870","0890":"0890","0849":"0849","0989":"0989","927":"0927","0844":"0844","Abergavenny, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Abergavenny, Monmouthshire, Wales","Much Marcle, Herefordshire, England":"Much Marcle, Herefordshire, England","Dorset, England":"Dorset, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Hamlin","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Irish: of Norman origin, from the Norman French and Middle English personal name <i>Hamelin</i>, a double diminutive of <i>Hamo</i> (see   Hammond  ).","French: variant of   Hamelin   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this.","Americanized form of Finnish <b>Hämäläinen</b> (see   Hamalainen  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Hamling","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Hamlin  ."]},{"name":"Hammond","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Middle English, Old French personal name <i>Ha(i)mon</i>, the oblique case form of the ancient Germanic <i>Ha(i)mo</i>, a short form of various compound names beginning with <i>haim</i> ‘home’. It frequently developed excrescent <i>-d</i>, giving <i>Hamond</i>, <i>Haimund</i>, and <i>Hawmond</i>. Alternatively, the name could derive from the Middle English personal name <i>Hamund</i> (Old Norse <i>Hámundr</i>, composed of the elements <i>hár</i> ‘high’ + <i>mund</i> ‘protection’), which may have been used in Normandy and in 12th-century eastern England, but the former explanation is more likely. The surname was sometimes confused with   Almond   and   Ammon  .","English: in the Bradford area of Yorkshire, the name is a shortened form of <b>Ormondroyd</b>, formerly <i>Hamondesrode</i>, from a lost place in Birstall (Yorkshire), named with the Middle English (Old French) personal name <i>Hamon</i> (1 above) + Middle English <i>roid</i>, a southern Yorkshire pronunciation of Old English <i>rod</i> ‘clearing’.","Irish: generally an importation from England, but occasionally an adopted name for <b>Mac Ámoinn</b>, see   McCammon  ."]},{"name":"Hamalainen","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Finnish Reino, Pekka, Aimo, Arvi, Jukka, Jussi, Olavi, Pirjo, Raija, Timo, Wiljo.","Finnish (<b>Hämäläinen</b>): habitational name for someone from Häme province, in central Finland. This is a well-established Finnish surname dating back to the 16th century. Compare   Hamlin  ."]},{"name":"Hamlen","meanings":["Found as a baptismal name. There does not appear to be any etymological connexion between this name and Hamnet. According to some the name in Hamlet's country was pronounced Amlet, and signifies 'madman' but no etymology has been suggested for such rendering. Amlet is the same name as Amleth, mentioned in the Danske Historic of Saxo Grammaticus, and Amlethus, King of Denmark and Sweden, found in Zedler's Lexicon. The name is from the Old German amal-laut, distinguished for spotlessness."]},{"name":"Hamblin","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Hamlin  ."]},{"name":"Hamlyn","meanings":["English (Devon): variant of   Hamlin  .","Americanized form of Jewish (Ashkenazic)   Hamburger  ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705175,"age":57,"year":"0927","julianDay":2059640,"title":"Kingdom of England is Formed","description":"Athelstan, king of Wessex and Mercia, formed the Kingdom of England.","url":"https://www.bl.uk/anglo-saxons/articles/how-was-the-kingdom-of-england-formed","urlTitle":"BL.UK - How England was Formed","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705176,"age":110,"year":"0980","julianDay":2078998,"title":"Vikings Invade England","description":"Viking raiders from Scandinavia invaded England in 980. Years later in 991, the English government paid them 10,000 in hopes for peace. The Viking raiders, however, continued to force more money from England.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Hamlin De Balladon was born about 0870, in Much Marcle, Herefordshire, England, his father, Dru de Baladon, was 28 and his mother, Mrs Dru de Baladen, was 22. He had at least 1 daughter with Mrs. Hamlin de Baladon. He died in Dorset, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"about 0870–":"umbes 0870–Surnud","0870–Male":"0870–Surnud","0874–Female":"0874–Surnud","0890–0989":"0890–0989","0844–Male":"0844–Surnud","0849–Female":"0849–Surnud","980":"0980","0874":"0874","0870":"0870","about 0870":"umbes 0870","0890":"0890","0849":"0849","0989":"0989","927":"0927","0844":"0844","Abergavenny, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Abergavenny, Monmouthshire